docs.lead_paragraph: We’ve all done it: Whether it’s about traffic, our boss or our partner’s annoying habits, complaining “is just something we do, like breathing — though hopefully not as often,” said Robin Kowalski, a professor of psychology at Clemson University.

headline.main: Go Ahead and Complain. It Might Be Good for You.

docs.abstract: Murders rose in 2019 for the first time in three years, yet they are still extremely low compared with past eras, and reports of other violent crimes crept up only slightly or declined.

docs.lead_paragraph: For the last several years, New York City officials have proudly claimed the title of the safest big city in the country. But for the first time in years, the crime figures for the last 12 months are threatening to undermine that sense of safety.

headline.main: The Truth About New York’s Rising Murder Numbers
headline.print_headline: Murders Creep Up in New York, but Crime Numbers Show Complex Trends

docs.abstract: Mr. Evans had prosecuted Mr. Flowers, a black man, in six different trials for the same crime. All either ended in mistrial or convictions overturned on appeal, and Mr. Flowers was released on bail in December.
docs.snippet: Mr. Evans had prosecuted Mr. Flowers, a black man, in six different trials for the same crime. All either ended in mistrial or convictions overturned on appeal, and Mr. Flowers was released on bail in December.
docs.lead_paragraph: For decades, Doug Evans, a white district attorney, was dogged in his prosecution of Curtis Flowers, a black man, for a 1996 quadruple murder in Winona, Miss., even as the case collapsed six times in mistrials or convictions that were reversed on appeal.

headline.main: White Prosecutor, Doug Evans, Asks to Recuse Himself From Curtis Flowers Case
headline.print_headline: Prosecutor Recuses Himself For 7th Try at Murder Trial

docs.snippet: To find Thai Cook in Elmhurst, enter the hot-pot place and take a right.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Queens neighborhood of Elmhurst is where you go when you want a Thai restaurant that will lead you to the dance floor and push you into dips and twirls that the places in Manhattan haven’t learned yet. You go there for Lamoon’s mango salad dotted with ant eggs, and Ayada’s chile- and garlic-laden raw shrimp.

headline.main: A Bangkok Kitchen Hides Inside a Chinese Restaurant in Queens
headline.print_headline: Anything but Your Usual Bangkok Kitchen

docs.abstract: The company had long maintained that the training wasn’t needed to fly the plane, which was grounded after two deadly crashes.
docs.snippet: The company had long maintained that the training wasn’t needed to fly the plane, which was grounded after two deadly crashes.
docs.lead_paragraph: From its inception, Boeing’s 737 Max was designed to save airlines the expense of training their pilots on flight simulators. During the initial approval of the plane and after two crashes killed 346 people last year, Boeing argued in conversations with the Federal Aviation Administration that simulator training was not necessary.

headline.main: In Reversal, Boeing Recommends 737 Max Simulator Training for Pilots

docs.abstract: The Patriots assistant had not been considered a top target, but he quickly emerged as the Giants’ choice. Matt Rhule, presumed to be the leading candidate, agreed to a deal with the Carolina Panthers.
docs.snippet: The Patriots assistant had not been considered a top target, but he quickly emerged as the Giants’ choice. Matt Rhule, presumed to be the leading candidate, agreed to a deal with the Carolina Panthers.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Giants, who joined the N.F.L. in 1925, have become known for a staid, prudent management style. True to form, on Tuesday morning, the team was expected to do something predictable: Hire Matt Rhule, the former Giants assistant coach who has become a rising star after rebuilding downtrodden college football programs at Temple and Baylor.

headline.main: Giants Agree to Hire Joe Judge as Head Coach
headline.print_headline: The Once-Staid Giants Turn to an Unknown
